dren from public areas at night. While many people celebrated the transition from darkness to light as the arrival of twenty-four hours of daytime, Baldwin shows that certain social patterns remained, including the danger of street crime and the skewed gender profile of night work. Sweeping us from concert halls and brothels to streetcars and industrial forges, In the Watches of the Night is an illuminating study of a vital era in American urban history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCities and towns -- United States -- History -- 19th century. 0aCities and townszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMunicipal lighting -- United States -- History. 0aMunicipal lightingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNight work -- United States -- History. 0aNight workzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNightlife -- United States -- History. 0aNightlife -- United States -- History.;Night work -- United States -- History.;Municipal lighting -- United States -- History.;Cities and towns -- United States -- History -- 19th century. 0aNightlifezUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226036038423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226036038.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles